<TITLE> Stocks close lower </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 28 (bdnews24.com) -- Dhaka stocks fell for the second day Monday as investors continued to trade in power and mutual funds shares. "The turnover board over the last couple of days shows that investors are changing their priorities, setting banks on the lower rung, and upholding mutual funds and power shares," said Moin Al Kashem from Prime Securities. Yaweer Sayeed, who manages over Tk 1 billion in funds at AIMS of Bangladesh, said: "The market is under pressure, this will persist until the shares from Jamuna and Megha are totally offloaded." Some banking heavyweights also drove trading. The Dhaka Stock Exchange's general index declined in the first hours of trading, remaining steady in the midday session, before gaining some ground towards the close. Stocks ended lower. The benchmark DGEN or general index declined 6.48 points, or 0.22 percent, to end at 2876.38. The DSI or all share price index closed at 2423.22, down 5.84 points, or 0.24 percent. The blue chip DSE-20 rose 0.36 points, or 0.01 percent, to end on 2311.20. Turnover climbed to Tk 1.29 billion, from Sunday's Tk 1.13 billion, from 12,659,851 traded shares. Gainers beat losers 132 to 97, with nine issues holding steady. Summit Power topped the turnover board, fueled by reports that the Securities and Exchange Commission may approve their issue of right shares. Summit Power closed 4.61 percent higher, at Tk 1575.25. Grameen Mutual Fund One continued its gain from the previous day, ending 2.68 percent higher, at Tk 99.40. State-run Jamuna Oil eroded Sunday's gain to end at Tk 357.70, down 2.71 percent. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh rose for the third consecutive day on reports of a deal with the government on the second fiber optic cable. It closed at Tk 684.75, up 1.78 percent from the previous day. Banking heavyweight BRAC Bank also continued its advance, closing 1.44 percent higher at Tk 1529.50. Among other scrips on the turnover board  AIMS 1st Mutual Fund and DESCO gained, while IFIC Bank, Meghna Petroleum and AB Bank fell. The day's major gainers were Chittagong Vegetable, Beximco Fisheries, BD Dyeing, Mona Foods and Al-Amin Chemicals. Padma Oil Company, UCBL, Trust Bank, Mercantile Insurance and BGIC topped the losers. Indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange ended mixed, with turnover increasing by over Tk 100 million. All sectors advanced, except cement, electrical, banking and miscellaneous. Ceramics, services & property and mutual funds gained the most. The CSCX or selective categories index surged 2.25 points, or 0.04 percent, to end on 4747.77. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7384.61, down 2.61 points, or 0.35 percent. The blue chip CSE-30 index climbed 13.45 points, or 0.20 percent, to end at 6604.39. Turnover on the port city's bourse rose to Tk 269.587 million, from Sunday's Tk 161.332 million, from 2,826,484 traded shares. Of the issues traded, 73 advanced, 44 fell and eight remained unchanged. bdn
